The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that electoral irregularities would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout all of southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe have not received them.
Instead, they have received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe have been victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats from the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is attributable to the villainous elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a result of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate, particularly in large parts of the rural areas.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, without being able to cast their ballot.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing observers at 52% of the rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
That means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
Even in this early stage, our previous investigations have revealed a pattern: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming body of evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is seen as illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The dispute over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were courageous and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Maybe it is not yet too late for that.
I write this text in sorrow, for Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to its end.
Perhaps the government wants to arrest me.
I was indeed already arrested before the elections for treason.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will to reclaim their rights and their power.
It is in our power to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
Should it come to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and see through to the end what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voices must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very difficult path together in order to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
You cannot simply leave these elections as they are, but you must also not fall into Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always a crisis somewhere because of elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to underhanded means when it is time to grant the people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I pledge not to leave it.
